<module>
  <title>proper nouns</title>
  <p>Proper nouns are <a href="?xx=nouns">nouns</a> which are also <a href="?xx=names">names</a>, identifying and referring to a single entity – a specific person, animal, place, organisation
    &amp;c.</p>
  <p>Like all nouns, proper nouns have a <strong>gender</strong> – they are either <strong>feminine</strong> or <strong>masculine</strong> –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><mark>Mairead</mark>
      <en>Margaret</en> and <mark>Sasainn</mark>
      <en>England</en> are examples of feminine proper nouns.</li>
    <li><mark>Seumas</mark>
      <en>James</en> and <mark>Bòd</mark>
      <en>Bute</en> are example of masculine proper nouns.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Since they refer to single entities, all proper nouns are <strong>singular</strong>. There are no <strong>plural</strong> proper nouns.</p>
  <p>Like all nouns, proper nouns are declined for <strong>case</strong> – they can have <strong>nominative</strong>, <strong>dative</strong> and <strong>genitive</strong> forms –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The dative and genitive forms of <em>Mairead</em> are both <mark>Maireid</mark>.</li>
    <li>The genitive forms of <em>Seumas</em> and <em>Bòd</em> are <mark>Sheumais</mark> and <mark>Bhòid</mark> respectively.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Like other nouns, proper nouns can be <strong>modified</strong> by an attributive adjective, e.g. <mark>Seumas Beag</mark>
    <en>Little James</en>, <mark>Mairead Bhàn</mark>
    <en>Fair Margaret</en>, <mark>Sasainn Nuadh</mark>
    <en>New England</en>.</p>
  <p>Like all names, proper nouns belong to different semantic classes, depending on the kind of entity they identify –</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Anthroponymic</strong> proper nouns name people, e.g. <mark>Mairead</mark>, <mark>Seumas</mark>.</li>
    <li><strong>Toponymic</strong> proper nouns name places (geographical entities), e.g. <mark>Bòd</mark>, <mark>Sasainn</mark>.</li>
  </ol>
  <h5>Anthroponymic proper nouns</h5>
  <p>Feminine anthroponymic proper nouns name female persons, <mark>Mairead</mark>
    <en>Margaret</en>, <mark>Caitrìona</mark>
    <en>Catherine</en>. They are slenderised, but not (necessarily) lenited, in both the dative and genitive cases, e.g. <mark>le Maireid</mark>
    <en>with Margaret</en>, <mark>taigh Maireid</mark>
    <en>Margaret’s house</en>. <boxlink ref="#feminine_anthroponyms"/></p>
  <box id="feminine_anthroponyms">
    <title>feminine anthroponymic proper nouns</title>
    <p>Feminine anthroponymic proper nouns name female persons. They are slenderised, but not (necessarily) lenited, in both the dative and genitive cases –</p>
